<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n36195e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36195e">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36195e"> 195(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ W<sup>m</sup> the Testy</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">His name, according to the most authentic etymology, was a corruption of Kyver; that is to say, a <i>wrangler</i> or <i>scolder</i>; and expressed the characteristic of his family, which for nearly two centuries, had kept the windy town of Saardam in hot water, and produced more <mark>tartars</mark> and brimstones than any ten families in the place; and so truly did he inherit his family peculiarity, that he had not been a year in the government of the province, before he was universally denominated <mark>William the Testy</mark>. <small> Washington Irving, <a name="WINY" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#WINY"><cite title="source">A History of New York, by Diedrich Knickerbocker</cite></a> (ed. unknown) 140</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
